JavaScript Testing
==================






















































Choices
-------

* karma - http://karma-runner.github.io/0.12/index.html

* jasmne - http://jasmine.github.io/

* mocha + chai - http://mochajs.org/ + http://chaijs.com/

... plus sinon - http://sinonjs.org/


My Choice
---------

* mocha + chai, bundled via konacha






































Syntax
------

* mocha provides testing framework syntax:

  - describe()

  - it()

  - before(), beforeEach(), after(), afterEach()

  - handles output styles
    eg dot: .....F....
    eg spec:
      Array:
        #indexOf:
          returns -1 when value is not present


* chai provides assertion syntax:

  - assert style, eg assert.equal(foo.bar(), "baz");

  - should style, eg foo.bar().should.equal("baz");

  - expect style, eg expect(foo.bar).to.equal("baz);


* sinon provides mocks, stubs, spies, fakes, etc

























Interesting Examples
--------------------

* Unit Tests


* DOM Manipulation

  - unless you are testing in browser, you need to BYODOM to your tests

  - option 1: DOM fixtures

  - option 2: make your widgets render their own DOM

  - pros / cons?


* Dependency Injection


* Spies, mocks, etc


* Dealing with bound functions


* AJAX Requests and Responses



























Conclusions
-----------

* JS testing is easy

* JS testing is useful

* JS testing tools are  mature

* JS testing is (dare I say it?) fun

* JS testing is something we should be doing










































